## HARDENING WAVE — 2026-07-13 (10/10 push: offline-completable hardening)
Scope: close every engineering-completable gap toward a 10/10 real-world readiness
that does not require a live instance, a Windows host, or an owner-gated npm
publish. Verified end-to-end: `npm run check` green (14 packages, 725 core + 943
mcp tests), all six governance gates pass, prod `npm audit` clean.

- [x] **HW-1. `completion` command (23rd CLI command)** — new
      `syncrona completion [bash|zsh]` prints a shell tab-completion script for the
      live command registry. Handler is completionCommand.ts (writes the script via
      `process.stdout.write`, kept byte-clean); registered in cliCommands.ts with
      bash/zsh choices + examples. README, CLAUDE.md and the CLAUDE-docs-drift gate
      updated (23 commands aligned with cliCommands.ts).
- [x] **HW-2. MCP output contract (`outputSchema` + `structuredContent`)** — the
      eight stable-shape tools (six session tools via `structuredJsonResponse`,
      plus `sync_status`/`sync_refresh` via `commandJsonResponse` on exit 0) declare
      an `outputSchema` and return conforming `structuredContent` on every success
      result (isError results exempt — the SDK v1.29.0 low-level Server does no
      runtime validation). Variable-shape CRUD tools intentionally excluded. The
      tool-reference generator renders an Output section per schema; contract +
      structuredContent assertions added to the mcp tests. Contract hash unchanged
      (ea90f026 over sorted tool names — schema additions never move it).
- [x] **HW-3. MCP stdio stdout purity** — for the protocol-channel commands
      (`mcp` inherits stdout as the JSON-RPC transport; `completion` pipes a script
      there), every bootstrap-phase notice is routed to stderr before loadConfigs()
      can log. bootstrap.ts `stdoutIsProtocolChannel(argv)` engages
      `logger.routeAllToStderr()` up front; mcpCommand.ts routes before setLogLevel;
      dotenv runs with `quiet: true`. 6 argv-parsing tests (bootstrap.test.ts) incl.
      `--log-level debug mcp` and the `--flag=value` form; the routing survives
      later setLogLevel rebuilds via a sticky flag.
- [x] **HW-4. MCP coverage gate raised to 90/80** — measured ~94.2% line / ~87.1%
      branch after the new handler/session tests; ratchet lifted from the prior
      floor. Core ratchet held at 92/79/89/92.

### Adversarial review of the wave (2026-07-13) — 3 findings, all fixed
A multi-dimension adversarial pass over the accumulated diff surfaced three real
defects (a Watcher requeue-stall candidate and two create-table-policy candidates
were verified and refuted). All three fixed with regression tests:
- [x] **REV-1. eslint-plugin linted the on-disk file, not the piped content** —
      packages/eslint-plugin/src/index.ts called `linter.lintFiles([filePath])`,
      re-reading raw disk bytes and ignoring the `content` it was handed. In a
      transform-then-lint plugin chain it validated the wrong (pre-transform)
      source; the sibling prettier/typescript plugins correctly operate on
      `content`. Fixed to `linter.lintText(content, { filePath })`; 2 tests that
      make disk and content disagree in both directions (previously masked because
      the tests wrote the same string they passed).
- [x] **REV-2. tool-reference generator degraded silently** — a non-inline schema
      value degraded the block to fallback parsing (dropping its Output section and
      param types) but neither generate nor `--check` returned non-zero, so the
      drift gate stayed green over an incomplete doc. Now fatal in both modes
      (consistent with extractToolBlocks' fatal spread handling); a CLI test covers
      generate-refuses and check-catches-a-committed-degraded-copy.
- [x] **REV-3. docs/VERSIONING.md said "22 commands"** — stale after the
      `completion` addition; the claims-drift gate only checks docs/index.html so
      CI missed it. Corrected to 23.

### Second adversarial pass (2026-07-13) — plugin-pipeline & offline-gate hardening
A follow-up multi-dimension audit of the build-plugin pipeline, the shared Jira
renderer, and the coverage-gate tooling surfaced seven more real defects (three
further candidates — a Watcher requeue stall and two create-table-policy paths —
were re-verified and refuted). All fixed with regression tests; `npm run check`
stays green (mcp tests 943 → 956; mcp coverage 94.13% line / 86.84% branch).
- [x] **REV-4. sass-plugin compiled the disk file, not the piped content** —
      `src/index.ts` re-read the entrypoint from disk instead of the `content` it
      was handed, so in a transform-then-compile chain it built the pre-transform
      bytes (the REV-1 class again). Fixed to
      `sass.compileString(content, { syntax, url: pathToFileURL(filePath) })` —
      extension-driven indented/scss syntax, and the file URL keeps relative
      `@use`/`@import` resolving against the entrypoint dir. 5 tests, incl. one
      where disk and content disagree and one resolving a relative `@use`.
- [x] **REV-5. typescript-plugin crashed on a tsconfig without compilerOptions** —
      a `tsconfig.json` with no `compilerOptions` key threw "Cannot set properties
      of undefined (setting 'rootDir')". Guarded by defaulting `compilerOptions` to
      `{}` before use. Regression test writes such a tsconfig beside the fixture.
- [x] **REV-6. typescript-plugin type-checked the disk bytes, not the content** —
      same REV-1 class: it type-checked the on-disk file while the pipeline had
      already produced corrected `content`. Fixed with an in-memory compiler-host
      overlay (getSourceFile/readFile/fileExists serve the passed content for the
      target file, delegating lib/node_modules to the base host). 2 tests make disk
      and content disagree in both directions; existing diagnostic behavior held.
- [x] **REV-7. babel-plugin mutated the caller's shared options** — it wrote
      `filename` back into the `options` object handed to every file in a build,
      leaking one file's identity into the next. Now builds a fresh options object;
      a test asserts `filename` never leaks into the caller's object.
- [x] **REV-8. babel-plugin treated empty output as a build failure** — the old
      `if (res && res.code)` guard failed a comment-only/empty source (whose
      transform is legitimately `""`). Now `typeof res.code === "string"` — empty
      output is a success. Test covers a comment-only source with `comments:false`.
- [x] **REV-9. jira adfToText threw RangeError on an out-of-range date** — a
      crafted ADF `date` node with a finite but out-of-range `attrs.timestamp` made
      `new Date(ms).toISOString()` throw, breaking the module's never-throws
      contract and aborting the whole issue fetch. Range-guarded (`|ms| <= 8.64e15`)
      to degrade to "" like every other bad input. Deterministic regression test.
- [x] **REV-10. check-coverage-gate.js silently ignored malformed flags** — a typo
      in a threshold flag (e.g. `--branch-threshhold 80`) left the gate at its
      default, most dangerously leaving the branch gate OFF (0) while the run still
      reported success. `parseArgs` now rejects unknown tokens and missing /
      non-numeric / out-of-0..100 values (and accepts `--flag=value`); a new
      `test/coverage-gate.test.js` (13 tests) covers both exported parsers.

### Third adversarial pass (2026-07-16) — full-repo sweep, 21 findings, all fixed
A third multi-dimension adversarial audit swept the whole monorepo (build plugins,
core pipeline, credential store, MCP runtime and its governance scripts) and
surfaced twenty-one real defects, every one adversarially re-verified (0 refuted).
All fixed with regression tests; `npm run check` stays green (core tests 740, mcp
tests 962). The recurring "operate on the disk file, not the piped `content`" class
(REV-1/REV-4/REV-6) reappeared in the last remaining build plugin, and two exit-code
and three governance-anchor bugs mirror earlier waves — evidence the sweep reached the
tail of each defect family.
- [x] **REV-11. webpack-plugin re-bundled the disk file, not the piped content** —
      `src/index.ts` ignored the passed-in `content` and re-read `context.filePath`
      from disk, discarding every prior transform in the chain (the REV-1/REV-4/REV-6
      class, now closed in the last build plugin). Fixed with an in-memory input
      overlay so webpack bundles the handed content. 2 tests make disk and content
      disagree in both directions.
- [x] **REV-12. babel-remove-modules leaked comment state across files** —
      `commentUsageTracker` lived in the plugin-factory closure keyed only by
      line+column (no filename), so one file's `@keepModule`/`@expandModule` usage
      bled into later files and tags were silently dropped. Reset per file in
      `pre()`; a test compiles two files whose tags share coordinates and asserts
      neither is dropped.
- [x] **REV-13. push --ci silently auto-resumed a stale checkpoint** — a leftover
      checkpoint made `push --ci` narrow (or entirely drop) the intended push and
      still exit 0. Now `--ci` validates the checkpoint and refuses a stale/mismatched
      one instead of silently resuming. Regression test drives the stale-checkpoint
      path.
- [x] **REV-14. resumed download blanked already-completed tables** — the skeleton
      force-write phase re-created completed tables as empty files, then the resume
      checkpoint skipped re-fetching them, so a resumed pull truncated the very
      tables it meant to preserve. Skeleton phase now leaves non-empty completed
      files intact (zero-byte still treated as missing). Tests cover forceWrite=false
      and ci mode.
- [x] **REV-15. webpack-plugin leaked compiler resources** — `compiler.run(...)` was
      never followed by `compiler.close()`, leaking webpack 5 caches, file handles
      and worker threads per processed file. Now closes the compiler in a `finally`.
      Test asserts close is invoked on both success and failure paths.
- [x] **REV-16. webpack-plugin swallowed config-load errors** — `loadWebpackConfig`
      caught every import error from `webpack.config.js` and returned `false`, so a
      config that exists but fails to load was silently ignored and the bundle built
      with default config. Now distinguishes "no config" from "config failed to load"
      and surfaces the latter. Regression test points at a throwing config.
- [x] **REV-17. non-atomic stale-lock reclaim let two pushes both acquire** —
      `acquireCollaborationLock` reclaimed a stale lock via a blind unlink+write, so
      two concurrent pushes could both win the collaboration lock. Reclaim is now
      atomic (ownership-checked). Test simulates the interleaving.
- [x] **REV-18. Table-API fallback marked 400/403/404 tables complete-but-empty** —
      a table returning 400/403/404 during the download fallback was dropped from the
      result yet marked complete and reported as "Download complete", leaving empty
      files. Now such tables are accounted as failures and set a non-zero exit code.
      Test drives each status.
- [x] **REV-19. findMissingFiles ignored flat layout** — it only checked the
      per-record folder layout, so `repair` reported every file missing (and
      re-downloaded the whole scope) in a flat-layout workspace. Now honors the
      configured layout. Test covers a flat-mode manifest.
- [x] **REV-20. failed push batch stalled with no retry** — after a failed push the
      in-flight batch was requeued into `pushQueue` but no drain was rescheduled, so
      the changes stalled forever. Now schedules a bounded auto-retry drain. Test
      asserts a requeued batch is drained again.
- [x] **REV-21. wizard source-dir produced an invalid config file** —
      `getDefaultConfigFile()` interpolated the free-text source directory into a
      double-quoted JS string with no escaping, so a backslash/quote in the input
      generated a syntactically invalid `sync.config.js` that bricked every later
      command. Now `JSON.stringify`-quoted. Test feeds a path with a quote/backslash.
- [x] **REV-22. docsCommand exited 0 on failure** — it logged failures via
      `logger.error` but never set `process.exitCode`, so `syncrona docs` reported
      success when generation failed or no manifest existed. Now sets a non-zero exit
      code. Regression test asserts the exit code on both failure arms.
- [x] **REV-23. instanceToFilename was lossy and non-reversible** — its `replace()`
      let two distinct instance names collide onto one credential file (silently
      overwriting) and could not be round-tripped by `filenameToInstance` — the class
      the twin `jiraProfileToFilename` was already rewritten with `encodeURIComponent`
      to avoid. Now reversible/collision-free. Test round-trips names that previously
      collided.
- [x] **REV-24. scope name unescaped in Table-API encoded query** — the config scope
      name was interpolated into encoded queries without `escapeQueryValue` (unlike
      `snClient.getScopeId`), allowing `^`-injection of extra conditions. Now escaped.
      Test asserts an injected `^` is neutralized.
- [x] **REV-25. buildRecordName didn't guard `.`/`..`** — it sanitized only `/` and
      `\\`, so a record named `.` or `..` wrote its field files outside the record
      directory (then `repair --apply --prune` deleted them). Now guards dot names.
      Test covers `.` and `..`.
- [x] **REV-26. config vm sandbox got the real stdout console** — the vm evaluating
      `sync.config.js` was handed the real stdout-writing `console`; bootstrap's
      stdout-purity routing only redirected the winston logger, so config-side
      `console.log` escaped onto the MCP/completion protocol channel. Sandbox console
      now routes to stderr. Test asserts nothing reaches stdout.
- [x] **REV-27. healthServer dropped its error listener after listen()** — the only
      `'error'` handler was removed once `listen()` succeeded, so any later
      server-level error had no listener and Node re-threw it, crashing the whole MCP
      process. A persistent logging handler now stays attached. Test emits a
      post-listen `'error'` and asserts no crash.
- [x] **REV-28. claims-drift auth gate matched a page-wide substring** — the
      auth-method documentation gate used a bare page-wide substring match, so the
      word "basic" (e.g. in "basically") satisfied the check even with Basic-auth
      docs removed. Now scoped to the `id="security"` section with word-boundary
      matching. Tests cover the "basically" false-positive and a missing section.
- [x] **REV-29. release-checklist section check was substring-loose** — required
      governance sections were checked with `includes(section)`, so a required
      `## Section` demoted to `### Section` (or buried in prose/a code fence) still
      passed. Now anchored to a line-start heading of the exact level. Test demotes
      every required section and asserts all are flagged.
- [x] **REV-30. claude-docs-drift section check was substring-loose** — same
      looseness as REV-29 for required CLAUDE.md sections. Now anchored via
      `hasHeadingLine`. Test demotes a required section to a deeper level and asserts
      it is flagged.
- [x] **REV-31. doctorCommand exited 0 on a broken workspace** — it computed
      `ok=false` when checks failed but never set `process.exitCode`, so
      `syncrona doctor` exited 0 while its sibling `checkEnvCommand` exited 1 in the
      same situation. Now sets a non-zero exit code on failure. Regression test
      asserts it.

Deliberately left ungated: internal snapshot docs (PRODUCT_STATE.md, VERSIONING.md)
carry point-in-time numbers (readiness/coverage/test counts) by design. The
user-facing claims (README, COMPARISON.md, index.html) are machine-gated by
claims-drift; PRODUCT_STATE.md's stale "22 commands" was corrected to 23 in place
rather than adding a fragile gate over a dated snapshot.

