## FULL REVIEW — 2026-07-01 (architect / dev / qa × 1 over the uncommitted hardening wave)
Scope: the working-tree changes (Jira client retry/guards, resolveConfig precedence,
credential health probe, encoded-query escaping, coverage gates, sn-transport TTL).
Ids continue the running ARCH-/DEV-/QA- numbering.

### Cycle 1 — Architect
- [x] **ARCH-10. Encoded-query escaping policy had too narrow a home and missed
      sites** — DONE 2026-07-01: `escapeQueryValue` lived in mcp-server's
      runtimeUtils.ts while the same interpolation class exists in core
      (snClient.ts:267 `scope=${scopeName}` from the project config file,
      snClient.ts:281 `user_name=${resolvedUserName}`) with no escaping at all,
      and two MCP sites missed the sweep: insightToolHandlers.ts:271
      (`tablename=${table}^documentkey=${sysId}` — both model-supplied args to
      the audit-history tool) and insightToolHandlers.ts:781
      (`sys_scope.scope=${scope}` in fetchScopeScriptRows, reached from
      compare-instances with a model-supplied scope). A policy that says "use
      this for EVERY interpolated value" but is only importable inside one
      package invites exactly this drift. Hoisted the implementation to
      sn-transport (its charter: shared SN policies that previously drifted via
      copy-paste), re-exported from mcp-server runtimeUtils (import surface and
      the new runtimeUtils tests unchanged), and applied it at all four missed
      sites.
- [x] **ARCH-11. CLI and MCP diverged on the null-Jira-config diagnosis** —
      DONE 2026-07-01: jiraCommands.ts:153-162 distinguishes an undecryptable
      stored profile (points at re-login via `jiraUndecryptableMessage`), but
      the MCP `jira_get_issue` (jiraToolHandlers.ts:70-72) always returned
      NO_JIRA_CONFIG_MESSAGE — the same failure produced contradictory guidance
      depending on the entry point. Mirrored the health probe in the MCP
      handler (`jiraCredentialHealth` is sync + never throws, fits the MCP
      resolution path).

### Cycle 1 — Dev
- [x] **DEV-4. 429 retry without a Retry-After header retried after 0ms** —
      DONE 2026-07-01: jira client.ts jiraFetch used `await sleep(wait ?? 0)`,
      so when the header is absent (proxies routinely strip it) the one retry
      re-hit the throttling server immediately — almost certainly a second 429,
      wasting the retry exactly in the case it exists for. Added
      DEFAULT_RETRY_WAIT_MS (1000ms) as the no-header fallback. Existing 429
      tests now pass a `Retry-After: 0` headers stub (which also exercises the
      previously-uncovered header-parsing path in retryAfterMs), and a new
      fake-timers test pins the 1s default backoff.
- [x] **DEV-5. isHexOfBytes doc comment contradicted its regex** — DONE
      2026-07-01: credential-store index.ts documented "[0-9a-f]" while the
      regex accepts uppercase hex too (`Buffer.from(x, "hex")` parses both, so
      the lenience is correct). In validation code guarding cipher input, a
      misdocumented rule invites a future "tightening" that would silently
      change behavior — comment fixed to say case-insensitive.
- Verified and cleared (no defect): `sinceDateTime`/`startedAtIso` raw
  interpolations are safe — `isoToServiceNowDateTime` re-serializes via
  `toISOString()`, output is canonical and cannot carry `^`; adf.ts block and
  inline recursion bounds are independent but each capped (max stack ≈
  2×MAX_DEPTH); branch.ts denylist loop cannot spin (regex cannot match
  zero-length); `comments: Infinity` flows only into a `slice` bound, not a
  URL; retryAfterMs handles empty/whitespace/negative/Infinity headers.
- Deferred (design observation, no change): with an explicit `--profile` that
  resolves no stored credentials, resolveConfig silently falls back to env —
  documented and strictly better than the old env-always-wins behavior, but a
  typo'd profile name can silently target the env-configured site. Consider a
  CLI warning when the explicit-profile fallback engages.

### Cycle 1 — QA
- [x] **QA-7. ARCH-11's MCP undecryptable branch had no test** — DONE
      2026-07-01: jiraToolHandlers.ts:72-79 (re-login guidance when a stored
      profile exists but won't decrypt) was exercised by nothing — a revert
      to the misleading NO_JIRA_CONFIG message would have passed the suite.
      Added a node:test in jiraToolHandlers.test.js that plants an invalid
      `~/.syncrona/jira/default.enc` under a temp home (os.homedir
