### CONFIGURATION COMPLEXITY (DX8-DX11)

**DX8: Plugin discovery requires manual names**
- The user must know the "TypeScript plugin" is called "@syncrona/typescript-plugin" on npm.
- `syncrona plugins` shows some but does not help when adding new plugins.
- [x] Add `config add-plugin` — DONE 2026-06-21: new action on the existing
      `config` command (so no new top-level command). With `--plugin <name>` it
      resolves the plugin (short alias / full pkg / loose form), reports
      installed-vs-missing, and prints the `npm i -D` command plus a paste-ready
      `rules` snippet; with no flag it lists all first-party plugins and their
      install status. Catalog + resolution + rendering are a pure module
      (pluginCatalog.ts); 16 tests (pluginCatalog.test.ts). README + CLAUDE.md
      updated.

**DX9: Default includes/excludes hidden in code**
- The "sane defaults" live in defaultManifestConfig.ts; users must read source
  code to understand them.
- [x] `syncrona status` should show "Active includes/excludes" — DONE 2026-06-13:
      status prints "Config rules: N include, M exclude (defaults + overrides)"
      from the merged config. (Per-rule defaults-vs-overrides provenance and a
      `config show-defaults` subcommand remain as a deeper follow-up.)
- [x] `syncrona config show-defaults` — DONE 2026-06-14: new `config <action>` command; show-defaults prints built-in sourceDirectory/buildDirectory/pushConcurrency/refreshInterval + default include/exclude rule counts. Documented (README+CLAUDE.md, 18 commands); e2e test.

**DX10: `sync.config.js` rule order matters, but there is no validation**
- README: "Order your rules by MOST SPECIFIC extension first!" — users can get the
  order wrong and silently fail.
- Note 2026-06-12: a broken config is now a hard fail instead of a silent default
  fallback (CR20), and option names/types are validated (G2); rule-order
  validation remains.
- [x] `syncrona build --check-config` — DONE 2026-06-13 (acb386e): validates rule
      order, reports any rule shadowed by an earlier broader one (synthesizes a
      representative filename from anchored patterns; zero false positives),
      exits non-zero without building. checkRuleOrder + 4 tests.
- [x] `--verbose build` — DONE 2026-06-13 (9c34412): processFile logs the matched rule per file at debug level.

**DX11: Advanced options undocumented (`displayField`, `differentiatorField`)**
- TableOptions get one line in the README. When to use them? What is
  `differentiatorField` for?
- "Will break the Windows filesystem" is a bad signal.
- [x] Document use cases — DONE 2026-06-13: README Table Options now has a
      "When to use each option" subsection explaining displayField (folder name
      field), differentiatorField (dedup of equal display values, with array
      fallback), and query (scope down large tables), plus a sharper Windows/WSL
      warning on differentiatorField.

