### WORKFLOW & DEVELOPER EXPERIENCE (DX16-DX18)

**DX16: Manifest refresh interval is hidden config**
- `refreshInterval: 30` is the default. A user on a slow network suffers.
- No clear documentation of what the 30-second refresh does.
- Note 2026-06-12: overlapping interval refreshes are now guarded (CR11).
- [x] Document refresh behavior — DONE 2026-06-13: README "Manifest refresh in dev mode" (30s default, overlap-guarded, --refresh-interval to tune/disable, debug timing).
- [x] `--verbose dev` should print "Manifest refresh took Xms" — DONE 2026-06-13:
      the refresher logs `Manifest refresh took Xms` at debug level (DX21).
- [x] A `syncrona dev --refresh-interval 60` flag — DONE 2026-06-13:
      `dev --refresh-interval N` (alias --refreshInterval) overrides
      sync.config.js refreshInterval; 0 disables polling.

**DX17: The file structure is strange for new users**
- "Records are shown as folders…", but users expect a flat structure
  (src/scripts/my.js).
- [~] `--flat` mode — CORE DONE 2026-06-21: lossless, reversible conversion
      (flatLayout.ts folderRelToFlat / flatRelToFolder, `~` field separator since
      it never appears in a dictionary field name; 13 round-trip tests) + `flat`
      config flag (shape-validated, getFlatMode) + README "Flat layout" docs.
      REMAINING: the automatic pull/push pipeline wiring touches the hot
      getFileContextFromPath parser + the write path and needs a live round-trip
      against an instance to validate safely — kept as an opt-in preview until then.

**DX18: Error recovery is undocumented**
- Partial push failure (network dies). The user does not know whether a retry is safe.
- Note 2026-06-12: checkpoint/resume no longer leaves bogus state after a declined
  prompt (CR5); the lock is released even on errors (CR6); behavior is documented
  in the core README ("Push recovery and locking").
- [x] `syncrona repair` — DONE 2026-06-21: new command (cliCommands registry +
      repairCommand.ts) reconciles the manifest against local files — reports
      missing (in manifest, not on disk) and orphan (on disk, no manifest record)
      files. `--apply` re-downloads missing (reuses processMissingFiles),
      `--apply --prune` deletes orphans (confirm unless `--ci`). Report-only by
      default; `--dry-run` overrides `--apply`. 6 tests; README + CLAUDE.md (19 cmds).

